{"parse":{"title":"Grotesque (architecture)","pageid":11830755,"revid":786339406,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:172px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Gou%C3%A9zec_(29)_Chapelle_Notre-Dame-des-Trois-Fontaines_08.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Gou%C3%A9zec_%2829%29_Chapelle_Notre-Dame-des-Trois-Fontaines_08.jpg/170px-Gou%C3%A9zec_%2829%29_Chapelle_Notre-Dame-des-Trois-Fontaines_08.jpg\" width=\"170\" height=\"227\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Gou%C3%A9zec_%2829%29_Chapelle_Notre-Dame-des-Trois-Fontaines_08.jpg/255px-Gou%C3%A9zec_%2829%29_Chapelle_Notre-Dame-des-Trois-Fontaines_08.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Gou%C3%A9zec_%2829%29_Chapelle_Notre-Dame-des-Trois-Fontaines_08.jpg/340px-Gou%C3%A9zec_%2829%29_Chapelle_Notre-Dame-des-Trois-Fontaines_08.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"893\" data-file-height=\"1191\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Gou%C3%A9zec_(29)_Chapelle_Notre-Dame-des-Trois-Fontaines_08.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Chimerae on a church in <a href=\"/wiki/Gou%C3%A9zec\" title=\"Gou\u00e9zec\">Gou\u00e9zec</a>, France</div></div></div>\n<p>In architecture, a <b>chimera</b> or <b>grotesque</b> is a fantastic or mythical figure used for decorative purposes. Chimerae are often described as <a href=\"/wiki/Gargoyle\" title=\"Gargoyle\">gargoyles</a>, although the term gargoyle technically refers to figures carved specifically as terminations to spouts which convey water away from the sides of buildings. In the Middle Ages, the term <i>babewyn</i> was used to refer to both gargoyles and chimerae.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> This word is derived from the <a href=\"/wiki/Italian_language\" title=\"Italian language\">Italian</a> word <i>babuino,</i> which means \"<a href=\"/wiki/Baboon\" title=\"Baboon\">baboon</a>\".\n</p><p>Bridaham, in his book <i>Gargoyles, Chimeres, and the Grotesque in French Gothic Sculpture</i> points out that the sculptors of the Gothic cathedrals in the twelfth and thirteenth centuries were tasked by the Pope to be \"a preacher in stone\" to the illiterates who populated Europe at the time.  It fell to them to not only present the stories of the Bible but also portray the animals and beings who populated the folk lore of the times.  Many of these showed up as grotesques and chimerae, carved on the buildings.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Gallery\">Gallery</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Grotesque_(architecture)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Gallery\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul class=\"gallery mw-gallery-traditional\">\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Grotesque_by_Nathaniel_Hitch_-_2_Temple_Place._Embankment._London.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Grotesque_by_Nathaniel_Hitch_-_2_Temple_Place._Embankment._London.JPG/111px-Grotesque_by_Nathaniel_Hitch_-_2_Temple_Place._Embankment._London.JPG\" width=\"111\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Grotesque_by_Nathaniel_Hitch_-_2_Temple_Place._Embankment._London.JPG/167px-Grotesque_by_Nathaniel_Hitch_-_2_Temple_Place._Embankment._London.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Grotesque_by_Nathaniel_Hitch_-_2_Temple_Place._Embankment._London.JPG/222px-Grotesque_by_Nathaniel_Hitch_-_2_Temple_Place._Embankment._London.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"336\" data-file-height=\"363\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Grotesque by <a href=\"/wiki/Nathaniel_Hitch\" title=\"Nathaniel Hitch\">Nathaniel Hitch</a> on exterior of 2 Temple Place, London.\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tors_gate_1_Oslo_detalj.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/Tors_gate_1_Oslo_detalj.jpg/103px-Tors_gate_1_Oslo_detalj.jpg\" width=\"103\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/Tors_gate_1_Oslo_detalj.jpg/154px-Tors_gate_1_Oslo_detalj.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/Tors_gate_1_Oslo_detalj.jpg/205px-Tors_gate_1_Oslo_detalj.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1191\" data-file-height=\"1391\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Detail from Tors gate 1 in Frogner, Oslo, Norway. The Art Nouveau house by architect Syver Nielsen, 1913.\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Affe_Lorenzkirche.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Affe_Lorenzkirche.JPG/84px-Affe_Lorenzkirche.JPG\" width=\"84\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Affe_Lorenzkirche.JPG/125px-Affe_Lorenzkirche.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Affe_Lorenzkirche.JPG/167px-Affe_Lorenzkirche.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"1089\" data-file-height=\"1562\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Architectural monument, <a href=\"/wiki/Bayern\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bayern\">Bayern</a>.\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Spring_Hill_Library_(3).jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Spring_Hill_Library_%283%29.jpg/68px-Spring_Hill_Library_%283%29.jpg\" width=\"68\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Spring_Hill_Library_%283%29.jpg/102px-Spring_Hill_Library_%283%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Spring_Hill_Library_%283%29.jpg/136px-Spring_Hill_Library_%283%29.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2556\" data-file-height=\"4506\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>A red Brick and Terracotta Gothic styled Library, designed by Martin and Chamberlain and completed in 1893.\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Grotesque_(architecture)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Chimera_(mythology)\" title=\"Chimera (mythology)\">Chimera (mythology)</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Grotesque_(architecture)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class